tural interdependence and interaction of global and local forces shaping the Atlantic world. They reinterpret as specific local responses to global processes the conflicts between empires, within imperial relations, the formation of national states, the creation of new zones of agricultural production and the decline of old ones, and the emergence of liberal ideologies and institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAmericaxForeign economic relations. 0aSlave laborzAmericaxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryxEconomic aspectszAmericaxHistory. 0aSlaveryxEconomic aspectszAmericay19th century. 0aSlaveryxPolitical aspectszAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistory. 0aSlaveryzAmericaxHistoryy19th century. 4aHistory : History. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh1 aEcheverri, Marcela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEller, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFradera, Josep M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcia-Balañà, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía Mora, Luis Miguel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaviña, Javier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarquese, Rafael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiqueras, José Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTomich, Dale W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTomich, Dale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.151